We recommended to management the following:
The Inventory Committee prepare a Report of Physical Count of Local Road Network (RPCLRN) using the prescribed format;
The Municipal Accountant maintain subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network and prepare a lapsing schedule for the computation of depreciation for each component at the end of the year;
The General Services Office maintain a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all the roads and their components; and
The Municipal Accountant ensure that the required disclosures are included in the notes to the financial statements.

We recommended the following:

The Accounting Office and MGSO shall perform reconciliation between their records of Road Networks. Any discrepancies found shall be verified, investigated and adjusted in the books of accounts, if necessary. Henceforth, perform periodic/regular reconciliation of property cards to ensure that all discrepancies are immediately investigated, cleared and reconciled with the books of accounts.  The LRN Ledger Card and Property Card shall always be reconciled with each other in compliance COA Circular 2015-008 dated November 23, 2015;

Municipal General Services Office shall prepare and maintain a Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components; and

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the Inventory Committee, Municipal Accountant, and MGSO to:

Prepare promptly the Report on the Physical Count of PPE (RPCPPE) and submit to the Auditor concerned not later than January 31 of each year; and

Maintain the prescribed stock cards/property cards and SLC/PPELC, and reconcile it with the RPCPPE to establish the correct amount of the PPE in the financial statements;

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

Require the Supply Officer to issue Inventory Custodian Slip (ICS) to end-users on small items with useful life of more than one year.;

Require the Municipal General Services Officer to maintain stock card to record all receipt and issuances of materials and supplies.;

Direct the Inventory Committee LGU to conduct annual physical count of inventories at the end of the year, and prepare the Report of Physical Count of Inventories which shall be submitted to the Auditor not later than January 31 of each year in compliance with Government Accounting Manual for LGUs.; and

Require the Municipal Accountant to provide disclosure in the Notes to Financial Statements in regards to the recognized expense incurred for the purchases of materials and supplies during the year in compliance with Government Accounting Manual for LGUs, Volume I.

Complete the reconciliation of the RPCPPE with the Accounting Office records to validate the accuracy of the PPEs, and to effect adjustment, if any, to appropriate PPE accounts;

Provide complete information in the RPCPPE, properly classify the PPEs according to their category and assign Property Numbers to all PPEs for easy identification especially during inventory-taking to determine non-existing/missing PPEs;

Prepare and maintain Property Cards for each class of PPE; and

Obtain pertinent records to dissect the items included in the subsidiary ledger for those PPE accounts presented in lump.

We recommended the following courses of action to Management to prevent accumulation of outstanding cash advances:


a) compel the accountable officers including the Municipal Accountant, Municipal Treasurer, Municipal Budget Officer and other concerned to immediately liquidate their cash advances otherwise, withhold the payment of the money due to these officials and employees as provided under Section 5.1.3, COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997 or demand full payment of the amount advanced to them specially those who had already separated from service;

b) instruct the Municipal Accountant to (i) stop granting of additional cash advances to concerned officials and employees unless the previous cash advances granted to them had already been liquidated; (ii) inform the AOs  that their failure on their part to comply herewith shall constitute “prima facie” presumption under Article 217 of the Revised Penal Code that they have malversed the funds to their personal interest and benefit (Martinez vs. Sandiganbayan, GR No. 126413 dated August 10, 1999). Likewise, their failure to liquidate within the prescribed period shall correspond to administrative liability with a corresponding penalty of suspension from government service enumerated under Section 5 of CSC Memorandum No. 23 series of 2019 and shall otherwise constitute violation of Article 218 of the Revised Penal Code for failure to render accounts and Section 89 of PD No.  1445 which is punishable under Section 128 of the same code; 

c) require the Municipal Accountant to submit summary of cash payments supporting the liquidation of cash advances to COA; and

d) strictly comply with the provisions of the abovementioned circulars to avoid the penalty stated thereon.

We recommended that Management:

a) strictly adhere with the documentary requirements as listed per COA Circular No. 2012-001 in the processing and granting of terminal leave benefits;

b) direct the Municipal Accountant to stop processing claims in the absence or lack of supporting documents, particularly those appointive and elective officials who were not issued clearance from properly, money and legal accountabilities;

c) strictly require settlement of any remaining liabilities of former officials and employees prior to the issuance of clearance; and


d) require the immediate submission of all lacking documents for each of the terminal leave benefit claims of former officials and employees.

We recommended the following:

The Accounting Office and MGSO shall perform reconciliation between their records of Road Networks. Any discrepancies found shall be verified, investigated and adjusted in the books of accounts, if necessary. Henceforth, perform periodic/regular reconciliation of property cards to ensure that all discrepancies are immediately investigated, cleared and reconciled with the books of accounts.  The LRN Ledger Card and Property Card shall always be reconciled with each other in compliance COA Circular 2015-008 dated November 23, 2015;

Municipal General Services Office shall prepare and maintain a Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components; and

We recommended that the Management:
Submit the said lacking documentary requirements as shown in the attached schedule (Annex H);
Submit justification/explanation on the other noted deficiencies;
Strictly comply with the rules and regulations on procurement as provided under the 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184; and
Ensure completeness and propriety of the required supporting documents for all disbursements in accordance with Section 4 of PD No. 1145, COA Circular 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012, and such other applicable laws, rules and regulations.

We recommended the Management to instruct the Municipal Accountant to:
effect the following proposed entry to correct the Construction in Progress accounts;
facilitate the immediate transfer of the completed projects to their respective PPE accounts in accordance with Section 50 of MNGAS for LGUs, Volume I, and ensure that only capitalizable expenditures are being charged to CIP accounts as prescribed in paragraph 23 of IPSAS No. 17 Property, Plant, and Equipment;
require the Municipal Engineer to provide the certificate of completion for all the completed projects by administration amounting to ₱8,350,118.10 and provide the same to MAO for recording and the Provincial Auditor’s Office for review of technical evaluation and inspection purposes together with the approved plans and specifications; and
direct the Municipal Accountant to transfer the 31 completed projects by administration from CIP accounts to their respective Infrastructure Asset accounts and Buildings and Other Structure accounts in compliance with IPSAS No. 1 and Section 50 of MNGAS for LGUs, Volume II.

We recommended that the Management instruct the:
Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the Municipal Treasurer, i) confirm from the concerned suppliers, officers and employees the said payables and require them to submit documents pertaining to their claims, otherwise, request its reversion from the Sangguniang Bayan (SB);
Municipal Accountant (i) in case the named creditors fail to support their claims, revert the amount to the unappropriated surplus of the GF upon approval of the SB; (ii) prepare a corresponding registry solely for the reverted accounts payable for recording and reporting purposes to keep track of all the reverted accounts payable and for the payment of the reverted accounts payable for future claims; (iii) provide sufficient justification as to the establishment of the ₱155,285.65 Due from Officers and Employees account charged to the former Municipal Treasurer; and (iv) transfer the amount of ₱155,285.65 from the SEF to GF and establish the receivables from the former Municipal Treasurer in the General Fund:

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the Inventory Committee, Municipal Accountant, and MGSO to:
Prepare promptly the Report on the Physical Count of PPE (RPCPPE) and submit to the Auditor concerned not later than January 31 of each year; and
Maintain the prescribed stock cards/property cards and SLC/PPELC, and reconcile it with the RPCPPE to establish the correct amount of the PPE in the financial statements;

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Verify/check the amounts in liquidation reports submitted to the Provincial Accountant of fund transfers with discrepancies in the balance recorded in the books of the Province;
Determine the status of liquidations of unsettled fund transfers reflected in the books of the Province that has been fully liquidated in the books of the Municipality, and if necessary, provide the Provincial Accountant of copies of liquidation documents that have been submitted so that the unrecorded settlement will be taken up in the books of the Province;
Cause the reconciliation of the inter-agency payable account Due to LGUs of the Municipality with that of the reciprocal receivable account Due from LGUs of the Province, and effect the necessary adjusting entries on the variance noted to reflect the correct balances of said accounts; and
Conduct a periodic reconciliation of inter-agency reciprocal accounts to ensure accurate balances of payable/receivable accounts in the financial statements.

